🧠 Factory Pattern — Final Notes
✅ Definition

Factory Pattern centralizes object creation and returns objects via a common interface instead of creating them directly using new.

🎯 Why we use it

Without Factory:

Payment payment = new UpiPayment(); // tightly coupled ❌

Problems:

Client knows concrete class

Hard to extend

Switch/if logic spreads everywhere

With Factory:

Payment payment = PaymentFactory.getPayment("UPI");

✔ Client depends on interface, not implementation
✔ Object creation is centralized
✔ Cleaner and scalable design

🧱 1️⃣ Basic Factory (Simple Factory)
Interface
interface Payment {
    void pay();
}
Implementations
class UpiPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("UPI Payment");
    }
}

class CardPayment implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Card Payment");
    }
}
Factory (with if/switch)
class PaymentFactory {

    public static Payment getPayment(String type) {

        if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("UPI"))
            return new UpiPayment();

        else if(type.equalsIgnoreCase("CARD"))
            return new CardPayment();

        throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid type");
    }
}
Usage
Payment payment = PaymentFactory.getPayment("UPI");
payment.pay();
⚠️ Key Insight

Factory does NOT remove logic — it moves it to one place

🧠 2️⃣ Improved Factory (Registry / Map-Based)

Removes if/switch from factory.

import java.util.*;
import java.util.function.Supplier;

class PaymentFactory {

    private static final Map<String, Supplier<Payment>> registry = new HashMap<>();

    static {
        registry.put("UPI", UpiPayment::new);
        registry.put("CARD", CardPayment::new);
    }

    public static Payment getPayment(String type) {
        Supplier<Payment> supplier = registry.get(type);

        if(supplier == null)
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Invalid type");

        return supplier.get();
    }
}

✔ No switch
✔ Easily extensible
✔ Better OCP support

🏭 3️⃣ Factory Method Pattern (No switch inside factory)
Factory Interface
interface PaymentFactory {
    Payment createPayment();
}
Concrete Factories
class UpiPaymentFactory implements PaymentFactory {
    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new UpiPayment();
    }
}

class CardPaymentFactory implements PaymentFactory {
    public Payment createPayment() {
        return new CardPayment();
    }
}
Usage
PaymentFactory factory = new UpiPaymentFactory();
Payment payment = factory.createPayment();
payment.pay();
⚠️ Important Truth

Switch is not removed — it is shifted outside

Example:

PaymentFactory factory = FactoryProvider.getFactory("UPI");
🔄 Factory Provider (runtime decision)
class FactoryProvider {

    private static final Map<String, PaymentFactory> factories = new HashMap<>();

    static {
        factories.put("UPI", new UpiPaymentFactory());
        factories.put("CARD", new CardPaymentFactory());
    }

    public static PaymentFactory getFactory(String type) {
        return factories.get(type);
    }
}
🧠 Key Concepts (Interview Points)
1️⃣ Coupling

❌ Before → Client depends on concrete class

✅ After → Client depends on interface

👉 Coupling is reduced and centralized

2️⃣ Open/Closed Principle

❌ Adding new type → modify if/switch

✅ Add new class only → no modification

class NetBankingPayment implements Payment {}
class NetBankingFactory implements PaymentFactory {}
3️⃣ Switch/If Statements

❌ Scattered across code

✅ Moved to factory / config / DI

4️⃣ Decision Making

Factory does NOT decide magically

Decision comes from:

Parameter ("UPI")

Config

Registry

Dependency Injection (Spring)

